    <Placemark>
      <name>Takkasilā</name>
      <description><![CDATA[<br><img src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/proxy/WAV0cCmCnoApCZSAfHIayha4YCfLzYqtXqp3tE-oxy71Kc_D4xV6KVddS4yz_fEzcfSTfnSIiSbVy5Czzh_Wx2o0xKXiuJvjf6NJMPSHZWhxYbKCnV2BYLIcJnoNHGDX8jAvn0vYyu5IdQOOMd378mu1fKt_l2qZY7p9TsZtuURJ9kSYzpZ7VuEZMlP4kFEPVhUag6txP2sajI_3mQZi4YkQ2CaKkfxYYXlvNHTha5DDp_EoqAkVJb9wcv6LeyTzt_aUuIMO0kuLo5E" height="auto" max-width="600" /><br><br>The capital of Gandhāra. The Vinaya describes it as the place of education of Jīvaka, the Buddha’s doctor (<a href="https://suttacentral.net/pi-tv-kd8">Vin.i.269f.</a>). <br><br>Takkasilā is identified with the Greek Taxila, in Rawalpindi in the Punjab.]]></description>
